LFT HL> Wainbow~<3 | trade.tf;-;Addictive and fun, Recommend dis
Mr. Nobody;-;Alright, it's been a long time since I decided to have a legitamite review of TF2 up, but I feel like it's time to bring one back. As a person who's sunk over 4,000 hours into this game, you're gonna bet this is gonna be a positive review. My old review was pretty damn cruddy in the first place, so I made it into a joke afterwards because it was the corniest pile of screws I've ever (very poorly) composed. My first point to make: The variety. 9 classes was enough for a ton of people to buy this game, even without hats, new weapons, or too many maps/gamemodes. If that's not enough, each gamemode has been updated to have atleast 3 maps, except for TC. TC only has one map, and that's TC_Hydro. The objective of TC is to advance a couple stages, capture the enemy's point, and protect yours. In other words, attack and defend (CP maps) minus the rest of the map. As mentioned earlier, a large amount of new content has spread around the game. With the sniper vs spy update, there came hats. Only a few, but still, hats. I wasn't there myself, but I can bet it would've been my new favorite toy. The weapons, which have been made at least once a year, are always a nice twist to the game. Adding a new form of strategy, offense, defense, and/or mobility, all weapons are a spice to that one bowl of noodles that make it seem like an entirely different game. My second point to be mentioned: How it was made. TF2 has an odd way of how it was first born, and how it eventually came to be what we love today. Starting as a simple quake mod made by 3 people, it's hard to believe that it became the TF2 that we (or I) love and know today. It grew pretty damn quickly, had it's own maps in quake, and was a huge hit in Quake, and Team Fortress Quake was probably the biggest leap in what lead to TF2's hype. Well, not TF2's hype. Valve eventually decided to accept them into them at their large success, and allowed the production of a game on the half-life engine. That was Team Fortress Classic. It was a higher balanced, smoothed, better quality game of Team Fortress. There's not much else to say about it. It's last update was 2004. The community had not completely given up on staying with TFC's system. A new game called "fortress forever." There's not much to say about it, it was a slightly better version of TFC. It never really did make it too far, considering TF2 came out only one month later. Since then, it has recieved multiple updates, changes, and/or tweaks on TF2. My third point that is well, the most interesting part of TF2 in my opinion: The lore. Yep, the lore. It's not well known to most TF2 players, and most hardly ever take note of it. Alongside the updates every once in awhile, TF2 always hides a little something that the community likes to take up on itself. The love and war update, for example. It had an ongoing line of hints that there would be an update revolving bread, and currently people believe there is a "engi vs spy" update coming up, based on game file updates. There's also comics that TF2 releases once in awhile. The mention of Jarate had a comic itself. I'm not going to go into much detail about the lore, because most of the fun of it is figuring the small things out yourself. The fourth part I, myself, find a major detail that TF2 really adds: Trading. Yeah, trading. It's gone downhill recently, and many are quitting because of this. I'm not going to go much detail about this, cause it's not really necessary in TF2 that you need hats, but being able to trade weapons and cosmetics is a large part of TF2. Being able to stem out in many directions, TF2's economy has grasped an interesting way to "donate" to the game creators. Especially Valve. Just know that when you buy something off of the Mann. Co store, the person who made that is payed, and you're increasing the development speed of HL3. The fifth part of this review is simply put: Community. Now, I can't stay positive with this entirely. TF2's community is, well, odd to define. TF2 is so far out there, that it grabs attention of a lot of people. It's jammed with weebs and bronies, not saying either of those are bad things (to everyone, I myself find both of those annoying at times), as most (MOST) of them stay sitting in their own servers. There's community-made maps, community-made hats, community-made guns, not saying that Valve's always too happy to accept those. That, or it's just trying to form a suicide pact. There are a lot of people in TF2, and it's hard to pinpoint what would define TF2's community, other than an ever-growing vast black hole, and it sure as hell isn't going down just because the trading is going down. The sixth and final part of this review: Extra stuff. If you don't like fighting in TF2, and aren't too happy with trading, then that's alright. There's tons of community created stuff that Valve DOESN'T accept into the game, that can still be ported into the game as a custom map, custom weapon, custom gamemode, or something of the sort. This can't really be put into a positive or negative form, as I'm happy with how some of this turns out, and some of it is, well, cannon fodder. Because the extra bits and pieces of TF2 are such a large piece of what makes TF2 so addicting, I'll be putting this into, well, just what it's meant to be. Extra bits and pieces. The weapons. These can be found pretty much anywhere. Whether it's on a times ten server, TF2 tightrope, hale, or weaponizer, most of these ideas are original, or simple modifications of a weapon. Most of these add a spice to it that fulfill a gamemode or class to maximize what it was made for and accept it as an additional piece of the game. When I say weapons, most of what has been claimed is well, a gamemode weapon. Yes, most of it's a gamemode weapon, and you have to play the gamemode to actually experience it. While it is rather strict, the TF2 community is always coming up with new stats, new models, and new ways to play the game with weapons via the workshop. The hats and cosmetics. This is probably going to be my shortest paragraph to exist on this review. It's via the workshop, Valve gives you examples on what to make it with, you make it, it gets accepted, you get some greens. Not paid mods, but, well, content that becomes official. The gamemodes. Whether it's forming TF2 into a horror game with a dark enviroment, somewhat scary unkillable bosses that crisp you alive; or dragging yourself against a slope at lightspeed with flashy lights and upbeat music, the gamemodes can easily turn what you thought was TF2 into something out of it's capacity. Now, when I say gamemodes, I don't mean non-competitive gamemodes. Those are gonna be in here for damn sure. Alongside weapons being added to fully experience a gamemode, there's also competitive gamemodes. Ultiduo, MGE, 6s, 4s, and Highlander. These gamemodes are also accomodated with websites with competitive TF2 involved, including UGC, ETF2L, AsiaFortress, and much more. There's badges, LAN tournaments, and bets placed on players that can easily turn TF2 into a fun non-profit game into a competitive, sweaty tryhard moshpit where you want to win with everything you got. Not saying that it really is that competitive, most TF2 competitive players are making jokes and get along pretty damn well in the community, but it does go large when the players make it. So, I guess that's my review on TF2, 8 years after it's release, still a large growing community with updates that supplies and endless amount of content that, well, does what it's made for. Scare you, infuriate you, or make you feel like you could dig your fingers into a tree because you play it so ed much, TF2's one hell of a game that I couldn't imagine ever dying out.
