The King;-;To put it shortly, Team Fortress 2 is a competitive multiplayer FPS with a loose spytech aesthetic, and is one of Valve's more popular monetary juggernauts. It was originally released in 2007 and was included in the Orange Box. Players choose from one of 2 teams and one of 9 classes, and must fight to complete objectives for their chosen team that vary by game mode. They can choose from a variety of weapons to aid in their missions, and wear cool hats while doing so if they so choose. Valve are still generously and freely updating the game even more than half a decade after it was released, with new bugfixes, maps, game modes and weapons. They should, however, take a break - more on this below. Objectives range from capturing and/or defending Control Points, to capturing enemy Intelligence while defending yours, to pushing large bombs along rails to destroy the enemy base, to banding together and fighting waves of killer robots and more. There is a lot of variety here, to say nothing of the custom maps and unofficial modes. Some of these are more prevalent than others, however - not every mode fits the game equally well. Players are able to randomly find, craft, purchase from the microtransaction store or trade for different weapons that they can equip. TF2 is not strictly pay-to-win because you are not required to spend money to gain weapons, although it may be the fastest way to get them. It's also worth knowing that the default weapons are generally good, and most of the other weapons are sidegrades. (Most of them, not all - a handful are still direct upgrades for some reason.) New players start off with only 50 inventory slots for any weapons they find. If a player wants more space - and they probably will considering how many weapons there are these days - they'll have to go Premium with a one-time microtransaction purchase. There is also a much larger amount of optional cosmetic items to put on your characters, acquired in largely the same way as the weapons. These are completely optional, but given that most TF2 players want to look pretty there is a sizable in-game trading 'economy' that largely focuses on these cosmetic items. Of note are the keys used to open Mann. Co Crates, which largely resemble a form of slot machine - except modern crates usually give you something nice. Kill-streak counters that grant graphical effects, weapons with persistent kill counters, different taunts and, of course, more hats. This is also completely optional and frankly an auxillary game function that I wish people wouldn't pay so much attention to. Keys also serve as one of the 'currencies' in the 'TF2conomy', and that's how Valve makes money from this game. Don't be put off by the hats - Team Fortress 2 has some good gameplay. The 9 classes are grouped into three categories, which are more like loose guidelines and should be regarded as such: The Attack classes are the fast and double-jumping Scout, the jack-of-all-trades rocket-slinging Soldier, and the flamethrowing ambushing Pyro. The Defense classes are the versatile, bomb-chucking Demoman, the Heavy Weapons Guy with the huge miniguns, and the Engineer with his helpful buildings. The Support classes are the really-quite-important Medic, the Sniper, and the backstabbing, disguising, cloaking, sabotaging trickster Spy. Most of the classes deliver differing gameplay experiences due to their abilities and mechanics. This means that you can play just one or two classes that you really like, or switch between any of the classes that your team or situation may need. This is because the classes largely serve to fill separate niches, and an effective team will contain a variety of classes - with some being more generally useful than others. (Given the nature of the game, you're bound to occasionally come across majority Spy and/or Sniper teams, which can be funny or annoying depending on your perspective.) TF2's general gameplay is slower than its Half-Life mod forebear Team Fortress Classic (and the original TF mod for Quake), especially when you compare player movement speeds. This is however balanced by the more tactical nature of gameplay. Overall tactics revolve around frontlines and offensive/defensive pushes, with the Medic's bercharges playing a vital role. Long-time veterans have also developed explosive-jumping strategies for the Soldier and Demoman that can rival the player mobility of TFC as they fly towards the front lines. This is, of course, assuming that you find a server with skilled enough players. Lower-level public servers (including most of the official servers) don't usually have the camraderie. Unfortunately, there don't seem to be as many around as there was back when new weapons were regularly coming out around 2011-2013. But, that could just be me. TF2 doesn't take itself too seriously, so you should be prepared to come across relatively easy-going players and matches as well. If you find yourself dissatisfied or complaining about a game like this, competitive TF2 is only growing stronger and pick-up games or lobbies are good places to play more seriously - or even enter the scene proper. With all this in mind, you could compare TF2 to a sort of MMO FPS. It had persistent items, and gameplay experiences that are built the same but can play out differently due to differing player tactics. Try playing the same 5 Control Point map for a while and you'll see what I mean. One other thing to note is that Valve treats this game as a test-bed: an area for testing ideas that might not work so well the first time around. This is just a useful thing to keep in mind. I also mentioned that Valve has continually added content to the game for most of its existence - from 2008 onward - which is especially admirable since they've taken to adding community-created content. Unfortunately, most of what they've been adding for a while now has been large amounts of community-created cosmetic items. Since there's several hundreds of them in the game now along with oodles of particle effects, weapons and other things...the size of the game has ballooned and optimization has taken a nosedive. I really hope they take time off from their stated 'content first' policy to do some housecleaning. Until then, you'll want a decently powerful machine to play this on - but avoid NVIDIA cards! They don't like this game's distinctive phong shading effect. Valve's balancing act is not perfect, either; they continually make changes & additions that are not always wise and that some of the playerbase love to argue about. Overall, though, the game is usually balanced enough to have fun with. While I recommend Team Fortress 2 as a great game overall, I must also recommend you avoid the old Steam Users' Forums board for the game. It's an insular, morose community of whiners who spam dumb memes and tired arguments, and the remaining moderators seem to have all but gone into hiding. If nothing else about TF2 interests you, please at least take my advice on SPUF.
