Allison! [deaf];-;Reviews for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing Re-reviewing. :) Overall Game TF2 is fantastic. There are a horde of game modes to play that can keep you coming back to this old game for a while. While I prefer MVM these days, I do often play community servers for a good CTF or payload round. Accessibility Gameplay Like most FPS games, TF2 uses WASD, space, and control. For mobility-related issues, keys can be easily rebound to whatever suit your capabilities. I rebound cruch to space and jump to a side mouse key, for example. As for sound, with the exception of spies and spy-related events (such as sapping of your equipment), there are visual cues to accompany the audio. For some weapons that you can hear being fired, you may not be able to see that you're being shot at (such as some sniper rifles). This is something to watch out for. For gameplay accessibility, I give it 10/10. You can realistically play and succeed at all of the normal (non-mod) game modes available, with or without sound. Subtitles & Captions For deaf/hoh gamers, TF2 offers subtitles and captions - something Valve has a solid history of providing. I've found the default captions lacking in MvM, however. Fortunately, there is a way to use external captions, and I have turned to clovervidia for that: http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=167785751 As a deaf gamer, I use captions over subtitles whenever I have the choice, as the distinction tends to be between important information in captions and flavor text in subtitles. That said, I have not used the subtitles option for TF2. For captions, I give it 6/10 normally, 9/10 with external captions (such as from clovervidia). Chatting/Communicating TF2 supports in-game voice communication, but the pacing of the game does not make it essential. Gameplay can tolerate typing, so many other players in servers tend to have no problem accommodating having to type. Even so, many game modes don't require much communication for casual play. For MvM, typing can be made difficult at times, and this problem can be exacerbated by queuing random teams each time you play and having to explain things repeatedly, which can be a gamble. I've written a guide to try to standardize voicebind calls in MvM until Valve changes voicebinds to be more inclusive, if ever. http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=358478951 Overall Accessibility TF2 incorporates visual signals for almost everything that happens in game. It's ability to rebind keys and add custom captions make it pretty accessible for most deficits in the gaming population. Overall, 9/10!
