Sonic | TWD Kenny;-;Ah, Team Fortress 2. Let's get down to the basics- TF2 is a class-based first person shooter made by a very successful company named Valve. Valve is the creators behind famous titles such as Left 4 Dead, Counter Strike, and Half-Life. TF2 started as a mod for Quake and slowly evolved. Over a 7 year editing period, TF2 was finally created and it was a HIT. To put this in retrospective, here is an example; Team Fortress 2 launched in 2007 and now it's 2014. This game just simply WON'T DIE! TF2 has 9 classes that are unique in their own way- each class having it's weaknesses and strong points, making every class equal and not over powered. These classes include, Scout - The nimble, fast-running, caffinated,  that can dominate the game (if the player is a good scout player), or can be taken out very easily. Soldier - One of the few classes that newbie players tend to pick first; Soldier uses a rocket launcher to take down his foes and gib them. Soldier has 200 HP and can be taken out with a few hits from the Scout's scattergun, but if played right, the Soldier can also dominate the team. Pyro, this unknown...thing... uses a flame-thrower to burn his enimies to a crisp and can be taken out, but normally it's taken out from a long distance. Pyro is great for close combat (same with the scout) and while he/she's not a class for newbie players, he/she can take out enimies within seconds. Demoman - A bomb-weilding drunk, that uses projectiles (bombs/stickies) to trap foes and/or stratigically place them to gib enemies. Demoman is NOT recommended for newbie players, AT ALL, but mostly because his tactics are very hard to get a good grasp of and he can take a LONG time to get used to and master. Heavy - The posterboy of TF2; the giant Russian man with a minigun. This big dude is (can be) one of the biggest threats in TF2 (as far as classes go) and can take down ANY of the 9 classes WITH EASE. By no means is the heavy overpowered, but he can definately get quite a few kills in. Heavy is also another newbie favourite and he's recommended for newbie players because of his very easy tactics and gameplay style. Engineer - The Texan wearing the hard-hat. Engineer (also referred as "Engie" or "Engy" *EHN-GEE*) uses Sentry guns, dispencers, and teleporters to fight in the battle. Engineer is also equipped with a shotgun, pistol, and a wrench. Engineer definately takes time to learn, master, and use, mostly because the player needs patience (building sentry guns take awhile to level up from 1 to level 3) and the player also needs to know when and how to use his/her sentry gun. Engie definately isn't a newbie-friendly class and will take some time to learn. Medic - The German medic that heals his dear comerades in the fight for victory. Medic is self-explanitory; he heals teammates in battle, but has different tactics of playing. The TF2 community has come up with a name for one of them,"Battle Medic," and this is used when a player uses Medic to fight using his needle gun (or his crossbow that is unlockable/craftable/buyable at any given time) rather than using his medi-gun to heal his teammates. Medic is an overall respected class and although he may seem a little complicated, he is a little newbie-friendly mostly because his point in the game is very easy to understand and he is overall an easy class to use. Sniper - The Australian sniper that isn't MLG :o The sniper (also referred after his name, "Mundy") is NOTHING like any other sniper you've ever played as. If you're a CoD player, transferring over into TF2, you'll be starting a new leaf because his gameplay is absolutely NOTHING like CoD or any modern shooter. First of all, there is no such thing as "quickscoping" or "360 headshot noscope" (unless you consider a hip fire to be a "noscope"). The sniper's gun doesn't give out an amazing amount of damage right as you scoper in, you need to wait a little while (there is a charge meter) until the sniper will do it's fullest amount of damage. Sniper's aim for the heads of their enemies and even if it's not a fully charged shot, the headshot will normally do 75-100 damage to any given foe. Sniper is almost ALWAYS picked by newbie players (especially CoD people transferring to TF2) mostly because his tactics and gameplay is amazingly easy and insanely simple to understand. Last class, Spy - Le Spy, the French guy who stole your mother,  your mother, and is right behind you. The Spy is adored by almost everyone. Being notorious for his backstab (If you backstab someone using your knife, it's an instant kill, dealing over 1300+ damage to any given foe), the spy can be a very sneaky class to choose and he can mean the life or the death of your team. If you know how to use the spy, you're more than likely to save your entire team, he's THAT powerful. On the other hand, if you're a newbie and you have no idea how to use the spy, your team will most likely fail because of a couple of reasons. Spies are generally targeted by most classes such as Heavy, Sniper, and Pyro, which means that if you're caught by the enemy team or you are revealed to the enemy team, you will be put on high alert and you will most likely find "Spy Checkers" (Spy Checkers are normally pyros who try to set their team mates on fire. If you're a Pyro on the Blue team and you use your flame thrower on a REAL team mate, the fire will not affect them and they will be fine, but if they use their flame thrower on a Red spy that is diguised as their team mate, they will burst in flames and you will be revealed.) checking their teammates. Spy is also a very hard class to master, which is why he's not recommended to newbie players. That's the general description of all the 9 classes you can choose from in TF2. Overall, TF2 is a GREAT, balanced, fun, and absolutely amazing multiplayer first person shooter that will never fail to impress. You will ALWAYS find someone playing the game, NO DOUBT ABOUT IT, and there are countless servers that are ran daily, ranging from Pub servers/Valve servers to custom made map servers. There are MANY ways to enjoy TF2 and you will certanly never feel bored because there is almost always something new to enjoy in TF2. TF2 has been an amazing game that has developed into something completely bigger than Valve had probably imagined. Thanks for reading my 10 hour long essay and novel, written by Sonic the Hedgehog | TWD Kenny. 10/10
